Comment: After beeing absent for a couple of months, I decided to start playing at gameknot again. Since my opponent had a low rating, I opened with e4-e5, although the scandinavian (e4-d5) is my favourite opening. I played quickly in the beginning, and due to that had nothing from the opening.  The crucial point of the game was at move 22. when white should have taken on c6 with his queen. But... see for yourself what happened.
Honestly, i dont know if I'd have any compensation if white played Qc6 here. My bishop at e7 would remain paralized.

f5! White is forced to Re1 since black threatens to take 2x on e4. 
After 25.exf5 Bxf5 white has no counterplay at all and is forced to inactivity. Black on the other hand, would have all the time in the world to try to improve his position.

Another fine move. The purpose is to bring the bishop to f6, and meanwhile cause another weakness in the white-kings camp. The alternate 27.Re2, is even worse since 27...fxe4, 28.dxe4 (Rxe4, Bf5..leading to a similar position discussed on the previous move) Bg4 captures the rook.

So much about my first game. I didnt know i'd have to go over such a long distance to beat a 1400 player, but at this moment i knew that the most of the job was done. The rest is technique. I'm especially glad about my play between move 22 and 28.
